{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> δείλαιος</b>, α, ον, <br /> (ος, ον [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “IG” 14.1722.7), lengthened form of δειλός (which see)\">Refs</a>]: — <b>wretched, sorry, paltry,</b> not in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Homerus Epicus, frequently in Trag., especially of persons, 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Prometheus Vinctus” 580 (Lyric poetry), etc.; δείλαιε τοῦ νοῦ 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Tyrannus” 1347 (Lyric poetry)\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; δ. χάρις a <b>sorry</b> kindness, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Choephori” 517 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; δ. σποδός <b>paltry</b> dust, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Electra” 758 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; δ. ἄχεα, ἀλγηδών, δύα, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Empedocles Poeta Philosophus 145, 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 513 (Lyric poetry), “Ant.” 1311 (Lyric poetry); γῆρας 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hecuba” 156 (Lyric poetry): sometimes found in Comedy texts (see. below) and Prose, 5th c.BC: Lysias Orator 24.23 (_superlative_), 4th c.BC: Aeschines Orator 1.172: in later Prose, 4th c.AD: Julianus Imperator “Orationes” 1.29b \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]. (The <i>penultimate</i> is short in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Antigone” 1311, “El.” 849 (Lyric poetry), 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Supplices” 279 (Lyric poetry), 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Equites” 139, “V.” 165, etc.) \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]","strongNumber":"G6787","accentedUnicode":"δείλαιος","shortDef":"wretched","mediumDef":"wretched","stepGloss":"wretched","stepTransliteration":"deilaios","count":0,"_step_Type":"word"}]}